184
00:07:17,840 --> 00:07:21,389
It directly returns the query results on the master node, right?

185
00:07:21,389 --> 00:07:22,469
In this scenario, there is an extreme possibility

186
00:07:22,469 --> 00:07:24,549
there is an extreme possibility

187
00:07:24,549 --> 00:07:27,380
your distributed system must consider extreme possibilities

188
00:07:27,380 --> 00:07:30,300
For example, the master node's clock gets suspended

189
00:07:30,300 --> 00:07:32,520
for example, it's hung for a few seconds

190
00:07:32,520 --> 00:07:34,940
During these few seconds of suspension,

191
00:07:34,940 --> 00:07:37,900
The master node itself is unaware that it has been suspended.

192
00:07:37,900 --> 00:07:41,000
Possible events like STW (Stop-The-World) may cause such issues, or similar events may lead to them.

193
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:42,560
